{"parse":{"title":"more","pageid":38117,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"more\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|more}}, from {{inh|en|ang|māra||more}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*maiʀō}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*maizô|t=more}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mē-|t=many}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|sco|mair||more}}, {{cog|stq|moor||more}}, {{cog|fy|mear||more}}, {{cog|nl|meer||more}}, {{cog|nds|mehr||more}}, {{cog|de|mehr||more}}, {{cog|da|mere||more}}, {{cog|sv|mera||more}}, {{cog|nb|mer||more}}, {{cog|nn|meir||more}}, {{cog|fo,is|meira||more}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{q|informal or nonstandard}} {{l|en|mo}}, {{l|en|mo'}}, {{l|en|moh}}\n* {{q|Internet slang}} {{l|en|moar}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|mô|a=RP}}; {{IPA|en|/mɔː(ɹ)/}}\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-more.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{enPR|môr|a=GenAm}}; {{IPA|en|/mɔɹ/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-more.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{enPR|mōr|a=rhotic,non-horse-hoarse}}; {{IPA|en|/mo(ː)ɹ/}}\n* {{IPA|en|/moə/|a=non-rhotic,non-horse-hoarse}}\n* {{IPA|en|/moʊ/|a=nonrhotic,dough-door merger,AAVE}}\n* {{homophones|en|moor|Moor|Moore<aa:pour-poor>|;|maw<aa:non-rhotic,horse-hoarse>|;|mow<aa:non-rhotic,dough-door>}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɔː(ɹ)|s=1}}\n\n====Determiner====\n{{en-head|det}}\n\n# {{comparative of|en|many}}: in greater [[number]]. {{q|Used for a [[discrete]] quantity.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There are '''more''' ways to do this than I can count.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2014-06-14|volume=411|issue=8891|magazine=w:The Economist|url=http://www.economist.com/news/science-and-technology/21604091-it-possible-sniff-out-problems-sewer-pipes-they-happen-its-gas|title=It's a gas|text=One of the hidden glories of Victorian engineering is proper drains. Isolating a city’s effluent and shipping it away in underground sewers has probably saved '''more''' lives than any medical procedure except vaccination.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200806170717/https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2014/06/14/its-a-gas}}\n# {{senseid|en|comparative form of much}} {{comparative of|en|much}}: in greater [[quantity]], [[amount]], or [[proportion]]. {{q|Used for a [[continuous]] quantity.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There's '''more''' caffeine in my coffee than in the coffee you get in most places.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-29|volume=407|issue=8842|page=72–3|magazine=w:The Economist|url=http://www.economist.com/news/international/science-and-technology/21580133-how-microbes-promote-liver-cancer-overweight-punch-gut|title=A punch in the gut|text=Mostly, the microbiome is beneficial. It helps with digestion and enables people to extract a lot '''more''' calories from their food than would otherwise be possible. Research over the past few years, however, has implicated it in diseases from atherosclerosis to asthma to autism.}}\n# Additional; further.\n#: {{ux|en|If you run out, there are '''more''' bandages in the first aid cupboard.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''More''' people are arriving.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I want '''more''' soup.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I need '''more''' time.}}\n# Bigger, stronger, or more valuable.\n#: {{ux|en|He is '''more''' than the ten years he spent behind bars at our local prison, as he is a changed man and his past does not define him.}}\n\n=====Antonyms=====\n* {{l|en|fewer}}\n* {{l|en|less}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|anymore|growmore|moredom|moreish|moreover|moresome|nethermore|neverthemore|overmore|uttermore\n\n|more haste, less speed|more confusing than a Rubik's cube|more royalist than the king\n|morefold|lies beget more lies|more-than\n|moreness|more money than sense|more than eleven|one more time|there's more than one way to fuck a cat\n|more power to someone|more dead than alive\n|more power to your elbow|have one more time|more grease to your elbow\n|there's more than one way to skin a cat\n|all the more|any more for any more|B-more|bite off more than one can chew|bollocks more like|couldn't be more different|cut off more than one can chew|delay no more|do more harm than good|ever-more|for ever more|have more chins than a Chinese phone book|have more chins than a Chinese phonebook|have more chins than Chinatown|have more money than God|honey catches more flies than vinegar|make the cheese more binding|meo more|more and more|more at eleven|more Catholic than the Pope|more cry than wool|more cushion for the pushin'|more dollars than sense|more equal|more heat than light|more honored in the breach|more is more|more kicks than ha'pence|more life in a tramp's vest|more like|more like it|more money than brains|more often than not|more power to your arm|more sacks on the mill|more sacks to the mill|more suo|more than friends|more than likely|more than meets the eye|more than one can poke a stick at|more than one can shake a stick at|more than one cares to mention|more than someone has had hot dinners|more than you can shake a stick at|more to the point|more-ish|more-or-less|need I say more|no more|no more Mister Nice Guy|no more Mr Nice Guy|no more Mr. Nice Guy|once more|once more into the breach|one hair of a woman can draw more than a hundred pair of oxen|one more time for the sweet souvenir|piss more than one drinks|please speak more slowly|slip into something more comfortable|some more|the tongue wounds more than a lance|there are plenty more fish in the sea|there's more than one way to cook an egg|there's more than one way to crack an egg|there's more than one way to peel an orange|there's more where that came from|those that have get more|those who have get more|what is more|what's more|you attract more flies with honey than vinegar|you can catch more flies with honey than vinegar|you can catch more flies with honey than with vinegar|you catch more flies with honey than vinegar|you catch more flies with honey than with vinegar|you get more with a kind word and a gun than you do with a kind word alone|have got more chins than a Chinese phone book|have got more chins than a Chinese phonebook|have got more chins than Chinatown|more important fish to fry|more sauce than meat|more than someone has had cooked dinners|need more time in the oven|no more no less|there are more horses' asses than horses|there's more than one way to feed a cat|one more again||more by token|nothing more than|sore boob means more boob|four more years|there are plenty more pebbles on the beach}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|comparative of many}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|meer}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|më}}, {{t+|sq|ma}}\n* Ambonese Malay: {{t|abs|lebe}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|أَكْثَر}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|اكتر|tr=ʔaktar}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|أَكْثَر|tr=ʔakṯar, ʔaktar}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|সৰহ}}, {{t|as|বেছি}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|больш}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|अधिका}}\n* Bourguignon: {{t|roa-brg|pus}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|по́вече}}, {{t+|bg|още}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|més}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|[[更]][[多]]|tr=gèng duō}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|víc}}, {{t+|cs|více}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|mere}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|meer}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|[[pli]] [[da]]}}, {{t|eo|[[pli]] [[multaj]]}}, {{t|eo|[[pli]] [[multe]] [[da]]}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|enemmän}}, {{t+|fi|useampi}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|plus}}, {{t+|fr|mieux}} {{qualifier|Saint-Étienne}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|plui}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|máis}}\n* German: {{t+|de|mehr}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐌼𐌰𐌹𐌶𐌰}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|περισσότερος}}, {{t|el|κι άλλος}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|πλείων}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|יוֹתֵר|tr=yotér}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|अधिकतर}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|több}}\n* Ido: {{t|io|[[plu]] [[multa]]}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|plus}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|più}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|...[[より]][[たくさん]]|tr=...yori takusan}}, {{t|ja|...[[より]][[多く]]|tr=...yori ōku}}, {{t|ja|[[もっと]][[多く]]|tr=motto ōku}}\n* Ladin: {{t|lld|plu}}\n* Latgalian: {{t|ltg|vaira}}, {{t|ltg|vairs}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|plus}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|vairāk}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|повеќе}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|lebih}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|കൂടുതൽ}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|aktar}}\n* Mansaka: {{t|msk|labi}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|илүү}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|chiù}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|pus}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|flere}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|fleire}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|mai}}, {{t+|oc|pus}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|بیشتر|tr=bištar}}\n* Picard: {{t|pcd|pus}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|więcej}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mais}}\n* Romanian: {{t|ro|mai mult}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бо́льше}}\n* Scots: {{t|sco|mair}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|motha}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|ви̏ше̄}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|vȉšē}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|viac}}, {{t|sk|viacej}}, {{t|sk|viacero}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|več}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|más}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|fler}}, {{t+|sv|flera}}\n* Tashelhit: {{t|shi|ati}}\n* Tocharian B: {{t|txb|allek}}, {{t|txb|auṣap}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|бі́льше}}\n* Uzbek: {{t|uz|ko’proq}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t|vi|nhiều hơn}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|pus di}}, {{t+|wa|dipus di}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|מער}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|comparative of much}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|meer}}\n* Ambonese Malay: {{t|abs|lebe}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|أَكْثَر}}\n* Armenian: {{t|hy|[[ավելի]] [[շատ]]}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|больш}}, {{t|be|яшчэ́}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|mui}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|повече}}, {{t+|bg|още}}, {{t+|bg|още}}, {{t+|bg|повече}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|més}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|多啲|tr=do1 di1}}, {{t|yue|再多啲|tr=zoi3 do1 di1}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|[[更]][[多]]|tr=gèng duō}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|víc}}, {{t+|cs|více}}\n* Dalmatian: {{t|dlm|ple}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|flere}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|meer}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|[[pli]] [[da]]}}, {{t|eo|[[pli]] [[multe]] [[da]]}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|enemmän}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|plus}}, {{t+|fr|mieux}} {{qualifier|Saint-Étienne}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|máis}}\n* German: {{t+|de|mehr}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|περισσότερος}}, {{t|el|κι άλλος}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|πλείων}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|יוֹתֵר|tr=yotér}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|több}}, {{t+|hu|még}}\n* Ido: {{t|io|[[plu]] [[multa]]}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|plus}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|più}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|...[[より]][[たくさん]]|tr=...yori takusan}}, {{t|ja|...[[より]][[多く]]|tr=...yori ōku}}, {{t|ja|[[もっと]][[多く]]|tr=motto ōku}}\n* Latgalian: {{t|ltg|vēļ}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|plus}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|vēl}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|lebih}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|илүү}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|chiù}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|mer}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|meir}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|بیشتر|tr=bištar}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|więcej}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mais}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|mai}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бо́льше}}, {{t+|ru|ещё}}\n* Scots: {{t|sco|mair}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|motha}}, {{t|gd|tuilleadh}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|viac}}, {{t|sk|viacej}}, {{t|sk|viacero}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|más}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|mer}}\n* Tashelhit: {{t|shi|uggwar}}\n* Tocharian B: {{t|txb|allek}}, {{t|txb|auṣap}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|бі́льше}}, {{t+|uk|ще}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|pus di}}, {{t+|wa|dipus di}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|mwy}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|en|comparative adverb}}\n\n# To a greater [[degree]] or [[extent]]. {{defdate|from 10<sup>th</sup>c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I like cake, but I like chocolate '''more'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I could no '''more''' climb that than fly!}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''More''' advanced students.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I have '''more''' than carried out my obligation.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I have no complaints and no '''more''' does my mom.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-07-19| author=[http://www.theguardian.com/profile/iansample Ian Sample]| volume=189| issue=6| page=34| magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly| titleurl=http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jul/08/irregular-bedtimes-affect-childrens-brains|title=Irregular bedtimes may affect children's brains| passage=Irregular bedtimes may disrupt healthy brain development in young children, according to a study of intelligence and sleeping habits.&nbsp; &para;&nbsp;Going to bed at a different time each night affected girls '''more''' than boys, but both fared worse on mental tasks than children who had a set bedtime, researchers found.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305121405/https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jul/08/irregular-bedtimes-affect-childrens-brains}}\n# {{senseid|en|used to form the comparative}} {{n-g|Used to form the [[comparative]] form of [[adjective]]s and adverbs.}} {{defdate|from 13<sup>th</sup>c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You're [[a great deal]] '''more''' beautiful than I ever imagined.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I am much '''more''' eager to help than you.}}\n#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=5|passage=Then we relapsed into a discomfited silence, and wished we were anywhere else. But Miss Thorn relieved the situation by laughing aloud, and with such a hearty enjoyment that instead of getting angry and '''more''' mortified we began to laugh ourselves, and instantly felt better.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=July-August|author=w:Henry Petroski| title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/2013/4/geothermal-energy Geothermal Energy]| volume=101|issue=4|magazine=w:American Scientist| passage=Ancient nomads, wishing to ward off the evening chill and enjoy a meal around a campfire, had to collect wood and then spend time and effort coaxing the heat of friction out from between sticks to kindle a flame. With '''more''' settled people, animals were harnessed to capstans or caged in treadmills to turn grist into meal.}}\n# {{lb|en|now|poetic}} In negative constructions: any further, any [[longer]]; [[any more]]. {{defdate|from 10<sup>th</sup>c.}}\n#* {{RQ:Malory Le Morte Darthur| book=XV| chapter=ii| passage=Than was there pees betwyxte thys erle and thys Aguaurs, and grete surete that the erle sholde never warre agaynste hym '''more'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|now|dialectal|humorous|or|proscribed}} {{n-g|Used in addition to an inflected comparative form.}} {{defdate|from 13<sup>th</sup>c.; standard until 18<sup>th</sup>c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I was '''more''' better at English than you.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|more or less}}\n* {{l|en|more so}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|comparative of much}}\n* Aghwan: {{t|xag|𐔼𐕀𐕒𐔺}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|أَكْثَر}}\n* Armenian: {{t|hy|ավելին}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|বেছি}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|бо́льш}}\n* Bourguignon: {{t|roa-brg|pus}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|повече}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|més}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|閣較|tr=koh-khah / koh-khà}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|更多|tr=gèngduō}}, {{t+|cmn|更加|tr=gèngjiā}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|víc}}, {{t+|cs|více}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|mere}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|meer}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|pli}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|rohkem}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|enemmän}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|plus}}, {{t+|fr|davantage|alt=davantage de}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|plui}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|máis}}, {{t|gl|chus}} {{qualifier|archaic}}\n* German: {{t+|de|mehr}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐌷𐌰𐌻𐌳𐌹𐍃}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|περισσότερο}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|μᾶλλον}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|વધારે}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|अधिक}}, {{t+|hi|ज्यादा}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|jobban}}\n* Ido: {{qualifier|before adjectives and adverbs}} {{t+|io|plu}}, {{qualifier|before verbs}} {{t|io|[[plu]] [[multe]]}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|plus}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|tuilleadh|m}}\n* Istriot: {{t|ist|pioûn}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|più}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|よりたくさん|tr=...yori takusan}}, {{t|ja|よりおおく|tr=...yori ōku}}, {{t+|ja|もう|tr=mō}}\n* Javanese: {{t+|jv|luwih}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|더}}\n* Ladin: {{t|lld|plu}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|magis}}, {{t+|la|plūs|n}}, {{t|la|abundantior|m|f}}\n* Mansaka: {{t|msk|labi}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|जास्त}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|дээр}}\n* Nepali: {{t+|ne|धेरै}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|pus}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|mer}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|meir}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|بیشتر|tr=bištar}}\n* Picard: {{t|pcd|pus}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|więcej}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mais}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|yalli}}, {{t|qu|aswan}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|pli}} {{qualifier|Rumantsch Grischun, Sursilvan}}, {{t|rm|ple}} {{qualifier|Sutsilvan, Surmiran}}, {{t|rm|pü}} {{qualifier|Puter, Vallader}}, {{t|rm|plü}} {{qualifier|Vallader}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бо́льше}}, {{t+|ru|ещё}} (when asking)\n* Scots: {{t|sco|mair}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|motha}}, {{t|gd|tuilleadh}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|viac}}, {{t|sk|viacej}}, {{t|sk|viacero}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|más}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|mer}}, {{t+|sv|mera}}\n* Turkish: {{t|tr|daha fazla}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|бі́льше}}, {{t+|uk|ще}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|dehana vêşi}}, {{t+|zza|tayna}}, {{t|zza|zeder}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|word to form a comparative}}\n* Aghwan: {{t|xag|𐔼𐕀𐕒𐔺}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Hebrew script: {{t|arc|טפי}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ավելի}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|daha}}, {{t|az|-rək}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|по|alt=по-}} (before adjectives and adverbs as a prefix), {{t+|bg|по́}} (before verbs, nouns and prepositions), {{t+|bg|повече}} (before verbs)\n* Burmese: {{t-needed|my}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|més}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|較|tr=khah / khà}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|更|tr=gèng}}\n* Comorian:\n*: Ngazidja Comorian: {{t|zdj|raha}}\n* Czech: (''uses a suffix'')\n* Danish: {{t+|da|mere}}\n* Dutch: (''usually uses the suffix'' {{m|nl|-er}}), {{qualifier|sometimes}} {{t+|nl|meer}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|pli}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|-mpi}} {{qualifier|comparative ending}}, {{t+|fi|enemmän}} {{qualifier|with some adverbs only}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|plus}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|máis}}\n* German: (''uses the suffix'' {{m|de|-er}})\n* Greek: {{t+|el|πιο}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{qual|adjective}} {{t|grc|-τερος}}, {{t|grc|-ίων}}; {{qual|adverb}} {{t|grc|-τερον}}, {{t|grc|-ιον}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|अधिक}}, {{t+|hi|और}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|-abb}}/{{t|hu|-ebb}}/{{t|hu|-obb}}/{{t|hu|-bb}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|plu}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|plus}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|níos mó}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|più}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|もっと|tr=motto}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|ជាង|tr=cieŋ}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|더}}\n* Lao: {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|plus}}, {{t|la|-ior}}, {{t|la|-or}}, {{qualifier|with some adverbs only}} {{t|la|-ius}}, {{t|la|-us}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|по-}}\n* Marathi: {{t+|mr|अजून}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|сайн}}, {{t+|mn|дээр}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|mer}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|meir}}\n* Persian: {{t|fa|-تر|tr=-tar}} (more beautiful: زیباتر)\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|bardziej}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mais}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|yalli}}, {{t|qu|aswan}}\n* Romani: {{t|rom|-eder}}, {{t|rom|po}} {{qualifier|before adjectives and adverbs}}, {{t|rom|maj}} {{qualifier|before adjectives and adverbs}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|mai}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|pli}} {{qualifier|Rumantsch Grischun, Sursilvan}}, {{t|rm|ple}} {{qualifier|Sutsilvan, Surmiran}}, {{t|rm|pü}} {{qualifier|Puter, Vallader}}, {{t|rm|plü}} {{qualifier|Vallader}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бо́лее}}\n* Scots: {{t|sco|mair}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: (''uses nas/na bu + suffix'')\n* Slovak: (''uses a suffix'')\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|bòlj}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|más}}, {{t|es|en [[más]]}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|mer}}\n* Tagalog: {{t+|tl|mas}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|อีก}}\n* Tibetan: {{t-needed|bo}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|daha}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|більш}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|زیادہ|tr=zyādā}}, {{t|ur|اور|tr=aur}}\n* Uyghur: {{t-needed|ug}}\n* Vietnamese: {{qualifier|after adjectives}} {{t+|vi|hơn}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|pus}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Amuzgo:\n*: Guerrero Amuzgo: {{t-check|amu|cheⁿ}}\n* Arabic: {{t-check|ar|أَكْثَر}}, {{t-check|ar|زِيَادَة}}, {{t-check|ar|أَزْيَد}}\n* Czech: {{t+check|cs|víc}}, {{t+check|cs|více}}\n* Dutch: {{qualifier|2}} {{t+check|nl|verder}}\n* Japanese: {{t+check|ja|もっと|tr=motto}}\n* Latin: {{t+check|la|plus}}, {{t-check|la|magis}}\n* Macedonian: {{t-check|mk|повеќе}}, {{t-check|mk|уште}}, {{t-check|mk|по-}}\n* Romanian: {{t+check|ro|mai}}, {{t-check|ro|mai mult}}, {{t+check|ro|încă}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+check|sh|još}}\n* Slovene: {{t+check|sl|več}}\n* Swedish: {{qualifier|1,2}} {{t+check|sv|mer}}, {{qualifier|2}} {{t+check|sv|ytterligare}}\n* Volapük: {{t+check|vo|plu}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{en-pronoun}}\n\n# A [[greater]] [[number]] or [[quantity]] (of something).\n#: {{ux|en|We’re running out of napkins. I should have bought '''more'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There isn’t enough salt in this. You need to add '''more'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I'd love to see '''more''' of Bob and Linda.}}\n# An [[extra]] or [[additional]] [[quantity]] (of something).\n#: {{ux|en|There aren’t many people here yet, but '''more''' should be arriving soon.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2016|author=Arun P. Mukherjee|chapter=English Studies in Contemporary India|editors=M. Sridhar; Sunita Mishra|title=Language Policy and Education in India: Documents, Contexts and Debates|page=254\n|passage=Speaking about Canada, where I teach, while the canon remains the ''raison d’etre'' of the discipline, some changes have come about and '''more''' are in the offing.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|title=Terms derived from ''more'' (pronoun)\n|less is more\n|more's the pity\n|more than one bargained for\n|say no more\n|the more the merrier\n}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|en|adjective}}\n\n# {{comparative of|en|many}}: in greater [[number]]. {{q|Used for a [[discrete]] quantity.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Last year’s applications received from new and returning students were '''more''' than each of the previous four years.}}\n# {{comparative of|en|much}}: in greater [[quantity]], [[amount]], or [[proportion]]. {{q|Used for a [[continuous]] quantity.}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|most}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|en|root}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|more}}, {{m|enm|moore|id=root|t=root}}, from {{inh|en|ang|more}}, {{m|ang|moru||carrot, parsnip}} from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*morhā}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*murhǭ||carrot}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*merk-||edible herb, tuber}}.\n\nAkin to {{cog|osx|moraha||carrot}}, {{cog|goh|morha}}, {{m|goh|moraha||root of a plant or tree}} ({{cog|de|Möhre||carrot}}, {{m|de|Morchel||mushroom, morel}}). More at {{l|en|morel}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|moor||dialectal}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|carrot}} {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[carrot]]; a [[parsnip]].\n# {{lb|en|dialectal}} A [[root]]; [[stock]].\n# {{lb|en|dialectal}} A [[plant]]; [[flower]]; [[shrub]].\n{{rfquote|en}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|moren}}, from the noun. See above.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[root up]].\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{etymid|en|back-formed singular of mores as in customs}}\n{{back-formation|en|mores}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈmɔː.ɹeɪ/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɔːɹeɪ|s=2}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q1115221}} {{lb|en|nonstandard}} {{singular of|en|mores<id:Q1115221>}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Michael J. Bugeja|chapter=[Influence] The Impact of Social Mores|title=Living Ethics: Developing Values in Mass Communication|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=w:[[Allyn & Bacon|Allyn and Bacon]]|year=1996|section=part I (Building Your Ethical Base)|page=15|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/livingethicsdeve0000buge/page/15/mode/1up|isbn=0-205-17323-3|passage=In the 1990s, smoking is considered dumb and a symbol of bad health habits, replete with the Surgeon General’s warnings. But even this belief is a social '''more''', subject to time. Maybe some future society will consider smoking brave—a symbolic affront to Big Brother government—or cowardly—a cop-out to avoid some type of community service.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Robert S. Pomeroy; John E. Parks; Lani M. Watson|chapter=[The MPA management effectiveness indicators] The socio-economic indicators|title=How Is Your MPA Doing? A Guidebook of Natural and Social Indicators for Evaluating Marine Protected Area Management Effectiveness|series=IUCN Programme on Protected Areas|location=Gland; Cambridge|publisher=w:[[International Union for Conservation of Nature|International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]]|year=2004|page=122|isbn=2-8317-0735-8|passage=A value is a social '''more''' or norm manifested as a result of history and culture. It is a shared understanding among people of what is good, desirable or just.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=David R. Caruso|chapter=Emotions and the Ability Model of Emotional Intelligence|editors=Robert J. Emmerling; Vinod K. Shanwal; w:[[Manas Kumar Mandal|Manas K[umar] Mandal]]|title=Emotional Intelligence: Theoretical and Cultural Perspectives|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:[[Nova Science Publishers|Nova Science Publishers, Inc.]]|year=2008|page=7|isbn=978-1-60021-856-9|passage=Given that emotions such as shame, guilt, embarrassment and others involve a violation of a social '''more''' or rule, these are often called the social emotions, self-conscious emotions or secondary emotions.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Barak A. Salmoni; Paula Holmes-Eber|chapter=[Dimension Five – Belief Systems] Some Features of Belief Systems|title=Operational Culture for the Warfighter: Principles and Applications|location=Quantico, Va.|publisher={{w|Marine Corps University}} Press|year=2008|section=part II (Five Operational Culture Dimensions for Planning and Execution)|page=189|isbn=978-0-16-083085-3|passage=In a seeming paradox, however, broken taboos may not always carry the heavy repercussions of violations of a social '''more'''.}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=emor|Mero|Omer|Orem|Orme|Rome|erom|mero|mero-|moer|omer}}\n\n{{cln|en|degree adverbs}}\n{{C|en|Celery family plants|Scandiceae tribe plants|Root vegetables}}\n{{cln|en|terms derived from the Proto-Indo-European root *merk-}}\n\n==Albanian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nAccording to Orel from the aoristic form of {{m|sq|marr}} without a clear sense development. It could also be a remnant of a grammatical structure of a lost {{der|sq|qfa-sub}} language, which may be the source of the same interjection found in all Balkan languages.<ref> Albanische Etymologien (Untersuchungen zum albanischen Erbwortschatz), Bardhyl Demiraj, Leiden Studies in Indo-European 7; Amsterdam - Atlanta 1997</ref> Alternatively, from {{bor|sq|el|μωρέ||mate|lit=stupid!|pos=interjection}}, a frozen vocative of {{m|grc|μωρός}}. In that case, it may be a {{doublet|sq|bre|nocap=1}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|sq|intj}}\n\n# [[man]]!, [[mate]]!, [[dude]]!, [[bro]]! ({{ng|vocative particle used in a call to a man}})\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nCan be placed before or after the noun, whereas {{m|sq|bre}} can only be placed after.\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|sq|mor|ore}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|sq|moj}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|ota|موره|tr=more|bor=1}}<ref>{{R:ota:Redhouse|موره|page=2028}}</ref>\n\n===Etymology 2===\nProbably borrowed from Southern Slavic [[море]] (\"sea\").\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|sq|[ˈmo.re]}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|sq|adjective}}\n\n# [[dark]] [[blue]]<ref>ngjyrë more (ngjyrë e kaltër e mbyllur), in: Fadil Sulejmani: Lindja, martesa dhe mortja në malësitë e Tetovës, 1988, faqja 174.</ref> Glossed as Polish [[szafirowy|szafirowe]] by Simon Kazanxhiu (ca. 1820).\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{l|sq|morre}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|sq|e kaltër}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Basque==\n{{wp|eu:}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eu-pr|+<audio:LL-Q8752 (eus)-Xabier Cañas-more.wav>}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{eu-noun|in}}\n\n# [[purple]]\n#: {{syn|eu|ubel}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{eu-ndecl|in}}\n\n===See also===\n{{table:colors/eu}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:eu:OEH}}\n* {{R:eu:EH}}\n\n==Czech==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|cs|noun form}}\n\n# {{infl of|cs|mor||voc|s}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology===\nDerived from {{m|da|moro||fun}}, which may be a compound of {{m|da|mod||}}, from {{der|da|non|móðr||mind}} and {{m|da|ro||}}, from {{l|non|ró||rest}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|/ˈmoːʌ/}} \n\n===Verb===\n{{da-verb|mor|more|morer|morede||moret}}\n\n# To [[amuse]], [[entertain]]\n# {{lb|da|reflexive}} to [[have fun]]; to [[enjoy oneself]]\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{da-conj|mor|more|morer|morede|h|moret|-|-|-|-}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|da|morskab|g=c}}\n* {{l|da|morsom}}\n* {{l|da|morsomhed|g=c}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:DDO}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nl|la|mora}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/ˈmoː.rə/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-more.ogg}}\n* {{hyphenation|nl|mo|re}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nl-noun|m,f|-en|+}}\n\n# the unit of length (short or long) in poetic [[metre]]\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nl|a=emor|moer|roem|Rome}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-cap-de-more.wav}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-more.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n* {{homophones|fr|mord|mords|mores|mors|mort|morts|qq6=general|maure|maures|qq8=one pronunciation}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|f}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|phonology}} [[mora]]\n\n===Adjective===\n{{fr-adj}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|dated}} {{alternative spelling of|fr|maure}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|fr|More|g=m}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|fr|orme|Rome}}\n\n==Friulian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{rfp|fur}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fur-noun|f|pl=moris}}\n\n# [[mulberry]]\n\n===Noun===\n{{fur-noun|f|pl=moris}}\n\n# {{lb|fur|phonology}} [[mora]]\n\n==Galician==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|gl|verb form}}\n\n# {{gl-verb form of|morar}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|^ò<r:DiPI>}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|it|noun form|g=f}}\n\n# {{plural of|it|mora}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|it|adjective form}}\n\n# {{feminine plural of|it|moro}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|it|verb form}}\n\n# {{lb|it|slang}} {{inflection of|it|morire||3|s|pres|ind}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|it|muore}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|it|a=emor|-mero|Remo|Rome|ermo|mero|orme|remo|remò}}\n\n==Latin==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{la-IPA|mōre}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|la|noun form|head=mōre|g=m}}\n\n# {{inflection of|la|mōs||abl|s|t=manner, custom}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:la:L&S}}\n\n==Latvian==\n\n===Noun===\n{{lv-noun|f|5|m=moris}}\n\n# {{lb|lv|archaic}} [[black woman]], [[blackamoor]], [[black moor]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{lv-decl-noun|mor|e|5th||||extrawidth=-60}}\n\n==Māori==\n\n===Noun===\n{{mi-noun}}\n\n# [[taproot]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|mi|tāmore}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:mi:Te Aka 3}}\n\n{{C|mi|Plant anatomy}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|enm|more}}\n{{inh+|enm|ang|māra}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*maiʀō}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*maizô}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|mare|moore}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmɔ̝ːr(ə)/}}\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmɑːrə/|aa=early}}\n* {{IPA|enm|/maːr/|aa=Northern}}\n\n====Determiner====\n{{head|enm|determiner}}\n\n# [[#English|more]]\n#* {{RQ:Malory Le Morte Darthur|version=WM|folio=35|lines=10–11|passage=Now is þ[er] ony ſeyde ''Marlyon'' that ye love '''more''' than a noþ[er]&nbsp;·}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|more}}\n*: {{desc|en-geo|mair}}\n* {{desc|sco|mair}}\n* {{desc|yol|more|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=mōr(e|pos=adj. (comparative)|id=MED28626}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|enm|root}}\n{{inh+|enm|ang|more}} and {{m|ang|moru|t=carrot, parsnip}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=mōr(e|pos=n.(1)|id=MED28623}}</ref> from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*morhā}}, {{m|gmw-pro|*morhu}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*murhǭ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*murhō}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|moore|morre}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/ˈmɔ̞ːr(ə)/|ref={{R:ang:Goering:2025|1-21}}}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{enm-noun|pl2=moren|pl2_qual=early}}\n\n# [[root]] {{gloss|of a [[plant]]}}\n#: {{syn|enm|rote}}\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} [[root]], {{gloss|of a [[hair]], [[tooth]], or [[tongue]]}}\n# {{lb|enm|figuratively|rare}} [[source]], [[root]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|more|id=root|qq=dialectal}}\n\n=====References=====\n<references/>\n\n{{C|enm|Anatomy|Botany}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|nb}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|nb|No-more.ogg}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{nb-verb-1|mor}}\n\n# [[amuse]], [[entertain]]\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*morhā}}, from {{inh|ang|gem-pro|*murhǭ||carrot}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|moraha||carrot}}, {{cog|goh|moraha}} ({{cog|de|Möhre}}).\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|more}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ang-noun|f|head=more}}\n\n# [[carrot]]\n# [[parsnip]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{ang-decl-noun-n-f|mor}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ang|feldmoru}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|ang|moru}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|enm|more|id=root}}\n* {{desc|cy|moron|bor=1}}\n\n{{topics|ang|Root vegetables}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA|móre}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|pt|verb form}}\n\n# {{pt-verb form of|morar}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|sh|/môːre/}}\n* {{hyph|sh|mo|re}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*moře}}, from {{inh|sh|ine-bsl-pro|*mári}}, from {{inh|sh|ine-pro|*móri}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{sh-noun|mȏre|n|adj=mòrskī}}\n\n# [[sea]]\n#: {{co|sh|od '''mora''' do Zlatibora|from the {{w|Adriatic Sea|'''sea'''}} to {{w|Zlatibor}}|inline=1}} (the territory of {{w|Zeta Banovina}}, i.e. greater {{w|Montenegro}}, comprising the Ijekavian part of {{w|Serbia}})\n#: {{coi|sh|od Timoka do '''mora''' Crnoga|from {{w|Timok}} to the {{w|Black Sea|Black '''Sea'''}}}} (the location of {{w|Stara Planina}})\n# {{lb|sh|by extension|preceded by preposition {{m|sh|na}}}} [[seaside]] or [[shore]] (any area or place near the sea where the sea is seen as the defining feature)\n#: {{ux|sh|Čim dođe ljeto, idemo '''na more'''!|Once the summer is here, we're gonna go '''to the seaside'''!|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|sh|Cijelo ljeto ću provesti '''na moru'''.|I will spend the entire summer '''at the shore'''.|inline=1}}\n# {{lb|sh|figurative}} a vast expanse or quantity of something, usually detrimental or unwelcome\n#: {{ux|sh|Ako se ne pozabavimo time sada, biti ćemo u '''moru''' nevolja!|If we do not deal with that now, we will be in a '''sea''' of troubles!}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|more|mora\n|mora|mora\n|moru|morima\n|more|mora\n|more|mora\n|moru|morima\n|morem|morima\n}}{{attention|sh|accents?}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* (''Croatia'', archaic) {{l|sh|morje}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|sh\n|okèān\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|sh|el|μωρέ|sc=Grek}}. Possible {{doublet|sh|bre|nocap=1}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{sh-intj|mȏre}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|Serbia}} {{non-gloss|when spoken sharply, asserts that the speaker is stronger or older or more powerful than the addressee, sometimes expressing contempt or superiority}}\n#* '''1824''', recorded by Vuk Stefanović Karadžić, ''Narodne srpske pjesme'':\n#*: {{quote|sh|»'''More''', Marko, ne ori drumova!« / »'''More''', Turci, ne gaz’te oranja!«\n|translation=»'''''More''''', Marko, don’t plow up our roads!« / »'''''More''''', Turks, don’t walk on my plowing!«}}\n# {{lb|sh|Serbia}} {{non-gloss|when not spoken sharply, functions as a term of endearment or generic intensifier, cf. {{l|sh|bre}}}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n''More'' is most often used in addressing a single male, more rarely when addressing groups of males, and more rarely still when addressing females.\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|sh|bre}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:sh:RJA|mȍre 1|4|7|id=jA8GcNJ1Mm}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Interjection====\n{{sh-intj}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|Croatia|Kajkavian|colloquial}} {{alternative form of|sh|može}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{sh-noun form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|sh|mora||gen|s|;|nom//acc//voc|p}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{sh-verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|sh|moriti||3|p|pres}}\n\n{{C|sh|Bodies of water|Landforms}}\n\n==Slovak==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|sk|ine-bsl-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\n{{inh+|sk|sla-pro|*moře}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sk-IPA}}\n* {{audio|sk|LL-Q9058 (slk)-TomášPolonec-more.wav|a=Bratislava}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sk-noun|n}}\n\n# a body of salt water, [[sea]]\n# {{lb|sk|colloquial}} a huge amount, [[plenty]] (+genitive)\n#: {{uxi|sk|máme '''more''' času|we have '''plenty''' of time}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sk-ndecl|n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col2|sk\n|morský\n|zámorie<g:n>\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sk:SDK}}\n\n{{C|sk|Bodies of water|Landforms}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|es|verb form}}\n\n# {{es-verb form of|morar}}\n\n==Tswana==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|tn|bnt-pro|*mʊ̀tɪ́}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|tn|/mʊ́ˈrɪ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{tn-noun|pl=mere|cl=3}}\n\n# tree\n#: {{syn|tn|setlhare}}\n# medicine\n\n==Welsh==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/ˈmɔrɛ/|a=cy-N,standard,colloquial}}\n** {{IPA|cy|/ˈmɔra/|a=cy-N,colloquial}}\n* {{IPA|cy|/ˈmoːrɛ/|/ˈmɔrɛ/|a=cy-S}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|cy|mutated noun}}\n\n# {{nasal mutation of|cy|bore||[[morning]]}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{cy-mut|bore}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|yol|mo'}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|more}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|māra}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/mɔːr/|/mɔː/}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|yol|adjective}}\n\n# {{l|en|more}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=8|page=86|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage='''More''' trolleen, an yalpeen, an moulteen away.|translation='''More''' rolling and spewing, and pining away.}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=86}}"}}